        "content": "<p>In quantum mechanics we are interested in 'square integrable functions'. I believe in Mathlib this corresponds to the type<code>MeasureTheory.Lp (α := ℝ) ℂ 2</code>. If I have got this right, this space should be equipped with an inner product. Am I correct in saying that Mathlib does not have this yet?</p>",
        "id": 501059613,
        "sender_full_name": "Joseph Tooby-Smith",
        "timestamp": 1740130151
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I forget the difference between that and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=lp#doc\">docs#lp</a>, though the latter certainly has an inner product</p>",
        "id": 501061541,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1740130742
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, that's the sum rather than integral case</p>",
        "id": 501061680,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1740130792
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Surely it's there? <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"644391\">@loogle</span> \"L2.inner\"</p>",
        "id": 501069769,
        "sender_full_name": "Luigi Massacci",
        "timestamp": 1740133002
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span aria-label=\"search\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f50d\" role=\"img\" title=\"search\">:search:</span> <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/MeasureTheory/Function/L2Space.html#MeasureTheory.L2.innerProductSpace\">MeasureTheory.L2.innerProductSpace</a>, <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/MeasureTheory/Function/L2Space.html#MeasureTheory.L2.inner_indicatorConstLp_eq_inner_setIntegral\">MeasureTheory.L2.inner_indicatorConstLp_eq_inner_setIntegral</a>, and <a href=\"https://loogle.lean-lang.org/?q=%22L2.inner%22\">3 more</a></p>",
        "id": 501069779,
        "sender_full_name": "loogle",
        "timestamp": 1740133003
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That should be it, I remembered there was a whole file for L2, it seemed unlikely not to have such a basic fact about it</p>",
        "id": 501070080,
        "sender_full_name": "Luigi Massacci",
        "timestamp": 1740133082
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you're only working with specific square integrable functions, and not the space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> as a whole, I strongly recommend using an ordinary function + the condition that it is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/MeasureTheory/Function/LpSeminorm/Basic.html#MeasureTheory.Mem%E2%84%92p\">MeasureTheory.Memℒp</a></p>",
        "id": 501073866,
        "sender_full_name": "Floris van Doorn",
        "timestamp": 1740134288
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Great many thanks <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"466290\">@Luigi Massacci</span> ! I don't know why I missed this.</p>",
        "id": 501091733,
        "sender_full_name": "Joseph Tooby-Smith",
        "timestamp": 1740140270
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"111080\">@Floris van Doorn</span> Alas, I want results about the whole of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. In particular, I have a particular set of functions in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and I want to show that they span the whole space. (Related to showing completeness of  eigenfunctions to the quantum harmonic oscillator)</p>",
